{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616608"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16406"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16406"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.83,0.03,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9097"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60136"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7117"},{"type":"tags","id":"7129"},{"type":"tags","id":"10378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old gentleman presents to his GP a year after a high speed motor vehicle accident where he sustained a severe traumatic brain injury. His mother reports that he hasn\u0027t been able to recall events that occured over the past year, since the injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following regions of the brain, if damaged, is most likely to impact episodic memory?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amygdala","Hippocampus","Hypothalamus","Cerebellum","Substantia nigra"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents with anterograde amnesia, which is the inability to form new episodic memories following brain injury. The pattern of memory loss is characteristic of hippocampal damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehippocampus\u003C/strong\u003E is critical for the formation and consolidation of episodic memories - memories of personally experienced events with their associated temporal and spatial contexts. Bilateral hippocampal damage results in severe anterograde amnesia while typically sparing other cognitive functions and older memories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in motor coordination, balance, and procedural learning. While it plays a role in some cognitive functions, it is not primarily involved in episodic memory formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubstantia nigra\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the basal ganglia and is primarily involved in movement control through dopamine production. Its dysfunction is associated with Parkinson disease rather than memory impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eamygdala\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in emotional processing and emotional memory formation. While it works in concert with the hippocampus, damage to the amygdala alone does not typically result in significant episodic memory impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E regulates homeostatic functions including temperature, hunger, and hormone release. It is not primarily involved in episodic memory formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hippocampus is essential for the formation and consolidation of episodic memories.","Damage to the hippocampus results in anterograde amnesia - the inability to form new episodic memories.","The temporal lobe, particularly the medial temporal structures, are critical for memory processing."],"references":["Anand KS, Dhikav V. Hippocampus in health and disease: An overview. Ann Indian Acad Neurol. 2012 Oct;15(4):239-46. doi: 10.4103/0972-2327.104323. PMID: 23349586; PMCID: PMC3548359.","Fortin NJ, Agster KL, Eichenbaum HB. Critical role of the hippocampus in memory for sequences of events. Nat Neurosci. 2002 May;5(5):458-62. doi: 10.1038/nn834. PMID: 11976705; PMCID: PMC4053170.","Raslau FD, Klein AP, Ulmer JL, Mathews V, Mark LP. Memory part 1: overview. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2014 Nov-Dec;35(11):2058-60. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A4059. Epub 2014 Jul 17. PMID: 25034776; PMCID: PMC7965175","Jawabri KH, Cascella M. Physiology, Explicit Memory. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554551/","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60136"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60136"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T10:18:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T10:18:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9097"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null